[underline][misc]misc_691|Geology Lecture 5[superscript]th[/superscript][/misc][/underline]
[misc]misc_689|Almost all the later Hypotheses is[/misc]
Cosmogony noticed in the former lectures
have in some manner led to the
acquisition of facts and to the
[underline]observation[/underline] of [underline]Nature[/underline] ._
The defenders of them have sought
for phaenomena subservient to their
own particular views.
The opposers of them have endeavoured
to discover appearances incapable
of being reconciled to the Theory

[page]8|MS-DAVY-11606-000-00008|dnp16f06pp|94870004[/page]
The real knowledge of the Earth has been
extended by the effects of both and practical
information has thus arisen from speculative
research.-
The objects connected with the
devellopement of a perfect chemical
Theory of the Globe are almost innumerable
Time and varied labour and the applicati[insertion]on[/insertion]
of great ingenuity will be necessary
for a general elucidation of causes
The foundations of the science however
are laid -
And the first principles [insertion]of Geology[/insertion] are sufficiently
distinct and intelligible.

[page]9|MS-DAVY-11606-000-00009|dnp16f07pp|94870007[/page]
Those principles which relate to the
[underline]properties of Nature[/underline] of the great masses
which compose the known part of the
surface the powers by which they are
modified and the order in which they
are maintained
When the general exterior of the
Earth is considered the appearances are
numerous and diversified. Hills and
Vales are seen green with vegetation.
Mountains hiding their summits in
the clouds and the light blue expanse
of water contrasted with the dark tints
of land: The view is warm with
beauty and [underline]animation[/underline].-

[page]10|MS-DAVY-11606-000-00010|dnp16f08pp|94870009[/page]
On penetrating [insertion]beneath[/insertion] the surface however
a new and altogether [underline]different[/underline] order
of things is presented to our attention
All is dark and silent -
Soils Earthy strata and Rocks are
blended together without regularity of
form - Veins of metalic ores and of
chrystalized stones intersect them in
different directions and by superficial
[underline]examination[/underline] deformity and disorder
only are perceptible in the subterranean
mineral [underline]Kingdom[/underline] -

[page]11|MS-DAVY-11606-000-00011|dnp16f09pp|94870011[/page]
This effect of confusion however is but
transient upon the [underline]investigating mind.[/underline]
For by Scientific methods of comparison
a distinct [underline]arrangement[/underline] is [underline]perceived[/underline]
even in those rudest [deletion]forms[/deletion] of the forms
of matter -
An analogy between their parts is
ascertained and their utility and
importance in the existing series of
Natural events appear great and
obvious.-
I mentioned in a former lecture that there
is a great resemblance in the mineral production
of extensive districts situated at distances
from each other.-

[page]12|MS-DAVY-11606-000-00012|dnp16f10pp|94870013[/page]
Similar soils and earths are usually
discovered incumbent upon similar stoney
strata and the various Rocks that occur
together in one position are likewise generally
found together in other positions.-
Thus the higher mountains of France
and [insertion]of[/insertion] [place]place_164|Spain[/place] are similar in their nature
to those of [place]place_159|Britain[/place]. Most of the specimens
brought from [place]place_878|America[/place] present appearances
of the same kind as those [deletion]brought[/deletion] [insertion]found[/insertion] [deletion]from[/deletion] [insertion]in[/insertion]
Europe -
And all the Rocks and stones that have
been as yet procured from [place]place_685|[underline]New Holland[/underline][/place]
a country containing so many novelties
[deletion]in Botany and Zoology have not[/deletion]

[page]13|MS-DAVY-11606-000-00013|dnp16f11pp|94870016[/page]
in Botany and Zoology have not any of
the characters of new mineralogical species
and precisely resemble those of the old
continent.-
It is on this circumstance principally that
our method of [underline]classing substances[/underline] according to
their Geological Relations are founded.
It is this circumstance which gives a
simplicity and [underline]an unity[/underline] to the arrangement
of the Science and which enables us to
judge of the position and nature
great masses from the examination of a
few of their [underline]minuter parts.-[/underline]

[page]14|MS-DAVY-11606-000-00014|dnp16f12pp|94870018[/page]
The distinction between the primitive and
the secondary Rocks have been already
often noticed and an attention to the
difference of their nature is of the highest
importance in every part of the study of
Geology.-
All substances that contain organic remains
that bear evidence of having been produced
since the existence of living beings on
the Globe are excluded from the series
of [underline]primitive[/underline] masses.-
As are likewise all strata fused by
volcanoes [deletion]fires[/deletion] or deposited from by
[underline]the agency of Water[/underline].-

[page]15|MS-DAVY-11606-000-00015|dnp16f13pp|94870020[/page]
[deletion]The primitive Rocks are[/deletion]
[underline]The primitive Rocks are[/underline] [underline]the substances[/underline]
which occupy the lowest part of the surface
of the Earth penetrated by human [underline]labour.[/underline]
And the form the summits of most of the
[underline]highest eminences of mountainous Countries[/underline]
The great masses of [underline]primitive Rocks[/underline] are of
[underline]several species[/underline] which have characters peculiar
to themselves and wholly different from those
of all other [underline]substances[/underline].-
These characters it will be necessary for
us particularly to attend to
They may be considered Geologically as two
Kinds.
The first are the external characters of
[underline]particular specimens[/underline] considered as to appearance
weight and hardness -

[page]16|MS-DAVY-11606-000-00016|dnp16f14pp|94870021[/page]
The second are the characters of the Rocks
considered as masses in the natural
[underline]connection[/underline] consisting of general [underline]form[/underline]
of fracture and of [underline]aspect[/underline].-
The characters gained from minute
inspection of single specimens are the
[underline]most accurate[/underline];-
But the general outline and shades of
Rocks though not uniformly to be trusted
to offer very  useful [underline]indications[/underline].-
I [underline]shall endeavour[/underline] to illustrate [underline]the[/underline]
[underline]first [/underline]class of characters by the exhibition
of pieces of Rocks.
And the second by means of Coloured
Sketches -

[page]17|MS-DAVY-11606-000-00017|dnp16f15pp|94870023[/page]
These illustrations will I fear be the most
tedious [underline]of the course[/underline] for accurate
Knowledge can only be gained by minute
inspection and in a Room so large as this
it is impossible that all the appearances
can be [underline]distinctly observed[/underline].-
I shall however use every effort to describe
the properties in such a manner that
they may be easily remembered and by
those who are desirous of acquiring
practical [deletion]knowledge[/deletion] information the
specimens may be afterwards examined
accurately [underline]and in detail[/underline].-

